            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Alina Sotomayor\u2019s life is a testament to quiet ambition and the power of a skilled, caring touch. Raised in Richmond by her African American mother and Afro-Puerto Rican father, a school administrator and a port mechanic respectively, Alina grew up in a household where hard work was the baseline and community was everything. She saw beauty not as a luxury, but as a form of self-respect and care, watching her mother\u2019s meticulous but simple skincare routine become a daily ritual of calm.\n\nWhile her friends pursued four-year degrees, Alina felt a pull toward a more hands-on profession. She enrolled in a community college program for Esthetics and Spa Management, seeing a direct line to a career where she could build something tangible. After graduating, she moved to San Francisco, taking a tiny room in a shared flat and a junior esthetician job at a chain salon. For five years, she honed her craft, building a fiercely loyal clientele who came for her immaculate waxing and stayed for her calming presence and expert skin advice.\n\nThe major turning point came when the owner of \"Verdant Skin,\" a boutique spa in Hayes Valley, poached her. Two years later, when the owner decided to move, she offered Alina the manager position. Now, at 37, Alina is the heart of the salon. She still takes her most dedicated clients but spends half her time managing staff, ordering inventory, and shaping the business.\n\nHer daily routine is grounded in the city's rhythms. She lives in a rent-controlled one-bedroom in the Inner Richmond, her sanctuary after a bustling day. The 5.5-mile commute on the 5-Fulton Muni bus is her time to decompress, listening to podcasts or simply watching the city wake up. Weekends are for long walks in Golden Gate Park, farmers' market runs, and quiet dinners with her small, close-knit circle of friends. Though she dates, her focus remains her career. Alina\u2019s dream is no longer just to work in a beautiful space, but to own it. She is diligently saving, crafting a business plan to one day open her own spa in a neighborhood like the Mission\u2014a place that reflects her bicultural heritage and her philosophy of accessible, holistic wellness for everyone."
